"use strict";(self.webpackChunkvedicskill=self.webpackChunkvedicskill||[]).push([[199],{64:(e,t,i)=>{i.r(t),i.d(t,{comp:()=>o,data:()=>n});var a=i(641);const s={},o=(0,i(262).A)(s,[["render",function(e,t){return(0,a.uX)(),(0,a.CE)("div",null,[...t[0]||(t[0]=[(0,a.Fv)('<h1 id="methods-of-probability" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#methods-of-probability"><span>Methods of Probability</span></a></h1><p>Here are the three main ways we assign probability, explained simply:</p><div class="language-mermaid line-numbers-mode" data-highlighter="prismjs" data-ext="mermaid"><pre><code><span class="line"><span class="token keyword">flowchart</span> TD</span>\n<span class="line">    A<span class="token text string">[Methods of Probability]</span> <span class="token arrow operator">--&gt;</span> B<span class="token text string">(Theoretical Probability)</span></span>\n<span class="line">    A<span class="token text string">[Methods of Probability]</span> <span class="token arrow operator">--&gt;</span> C<span class="token text string">(Emperical Probability)</span></span>\n<span class="line">    A<span class="token text string">[Methods of Probability]</span> <span class="token arrow operator">--&gt;</span> D<span class="token text string">(Subjective Probability)</span></span>\n<span class="line"></span></code></pre><div class="line-numbers" aria-hidden="true" style="counter-reset:line-number 0;"><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div></div></div><p><em>Fig 1.1: Methods of assigning Probability</em></p><h2 id="theoretical-probability-classical" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#theoretical-probability-classical"><span>Theoretical Probability - (Classical)</span></a></h2><p><strong>What it is:</strong> When all outcomes are equally likely, you count the favorable outcomes and divide by total possible outcomes.</p><p><strong>Examples:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Coin flip:</strong> 1 way to get heads รท 2 total outcomes = 1/2 = 50%</li><li><strong>Rolling a dice:</strong> 1 way to get a &quot;3&quot; รท 6 total numbers = 1/6 = 16.7%</li><li><strong>Drawing a red card:</strong> 26 red cards รท 52 total cards = 26/52 = 50%</li><li><strong>Lottery ticket:</strong> 1 winning combination รท millions of possible combinations = very tiny probability</li></ul><p><strong>When to use:</strong> When you know all possible outcomes and they&#39;re all equally likely to happen.</p><h2 id="empirical-probability-relative-frequency" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#empirical-probability-relative-frequency"><span>Empirical Probability - (Relative Frequency)</span></a></h2><p><strong>What it is:</strong> Look at what happened in the past and use that to estimate future probability.</p><p><strong>Examples:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Free throws:</strong> Basketball player made 80 out of 100 free throws, so probability = 80/100 = 80%</li><li><strong>Weather:</strong> It rained 12 days out of 30 days last month, so probability of rain = 12/30 = 40%</li><li><strong>Product defects:</strong> 5 broken items out of 1000 manufactured = 5/1000 = 0.5%</li><li><strong>Test scores:</strong> Student got A&#39;s on 7 out of 10 tests, so probability of getting A = 70%</li></ul><p><strong>When to use:</strong> When you have historical data or can repeat an experiment many times.</p><h2 id="subjective-probability" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#subjective-probability"><span>Subjective Probability</span></a></h2><p><strong>What it is:</strong> Based on personal judgment, experience, or opinion when you can&#39;t use math or data.</p><p><strong>How it works:</strong> You make an educated guess based on what you know and feel.</p><p><strong>Examples:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Sports betting:</strong> &quot;I think my team has a 70% chance of winning&quot; (based on team performance, injuries, etc.)</li><li><strong>Business decisions:</strong> &quot;There&#39;s a 60% chance this new product will succeed&quot; (based on market research and experience)</li><li><strong>Medical diagnosis:</strong> Doctor says &quot;80% chance this treatment will work&quot; (based on experience with similar patients)</li><li><strong>Job interview:</strong> &quot;I think I have a 30% chance of getting this job&quot; (based on how the interview went)</li></ul><p><strong>When to use:</strong> When you don&#39;t have exact data or can&#39;t calculate mathematically, but you still need to make decisions.</p><p>Each method is useful in different situations, and sometimes people combine them to make better estimates.</p>',21)])])}]]),n=JSON.parse('{"path":"/statistics/probability/method-of-probability.html","title":"Methods of Probability","lang":"en-US","frontmatter":{},"headers":[{"level":2,"title":"Theoretical Probability - (Classical)","slug":"theoretical-probability-classical","link":"#theoretical-probability-classical","children":[]},{"level":2,"title":"Empirical Probability - (Relative Frequency)","slug":"empirical-probability-relative-frequency","link":"#empirical-probability-relative-frequency","children":[]},{"level":2,"title":"Subjective Probability","slug":"subjective-probability","link":"#subjective-probability","children":[]}],"git":{"contributors":[{"name":"vedicskill","username":"vedicskill","email":"vedicskill@gmail.com","commits":1,"url":"https://github.com/vedicskill"}],"changelog":[{"hash":"3e7962b1467b8c9db47cbda2b963a336aeca3385","time":1757307553000,"email":"vedicskill@gmail.com","author":"vedicskill","message":"Merge pull request #7 from vedicskill/develop"}]},"filePathRelative":"statistics/probability/method-of-probability.md"}')}}]);